Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (for lay people)

accurately estimating statistical information: plot type plays a role

  • box plots: spread; distribution
  • bar/line plot: mean
  • modified stock chart: maxima, minima; spread (Albers et al., 2014; Pierce & Chick, 2013)
  • there is a lot of basic research on visualizing statistical information
  • however, when plotting ES a lot of these phenomena we know about on a small scale come together and interact
  • there is first evidence that the type of visualization we choose
  • plays a role as to how accurately lay people estimate statistical information

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (for lay people)

accurately estimating statistical information: plot type plays a role

  • box plots: spread; distribution
  • bar/line plot: mean
  • modified stock chart: maxima, minima; spread (Albers et al., 2014; Pierce & Chick, 2013)



supporting the process: enrichment options

  • benchmarks (anchoring) (Cohen, 1988; Jacowitz & Kahneman, 1995)
  • cues (signaling) (Schneider et al., 2018)
  • Enrichment options for these visualizations may further support the complex processes of sense-making
  • A common approach is to provide standardized benchmarks against which also researchers typically anchor their interpretations
  • research on multimedia learning suggests that the use of cues (e.g.Â arrows, labels) can direct observersâ attention.
  • This so-called signaling effect can increase understanding and reduce cognitive load

Background & Focus

Why looking at effect sizes?

  • “clearing house” approaches
    “best available [â¦] evidence from systematic research” (Sackett et al., 1996, p. 71)



  • evaluated according to the extent to which it allows to assess treatment effectiveness (APA, 2002)



  • Meta-analyses demonstrate highest level of evidence
    ES = key information to be communicated (Burns et al., 2011)
  • from an evidence-informed practice perspective
  • so called “clearing house” approaches
    try to make the “best available [â¦] evidence from systematic research” accessible to â¦
  • particularly evaluated according to the extent to which it allows to assess treatment effectiveness, i.e.Â the investigation of whether a treatment works
    so in our study we look at group differences
  • Meta-analyses = highest level of evidence
    ES = key information to be communicated

Background & Focus

Why designing science communication?



evidence
informed
practice

  • Teachers: encouraged to consider evidence from research (Slavin, 2020)



  • in their daily practice, they rarely draw on research evidence (e.g., Thomm et al., 2021)



  • current approaches: toward intuitive science communication
    (Farley-Ripple et al., 2020; Hedges, 2018)
  • Teachers are encouraged to consider evidence in their professional practice
  • teachers rarely draw on research evidence in their daily practice
  • different strategies exist to increase / foster teachersâ engagement with evidence
  • current approaches: toward a more intuitive science communication

Background & Focus

What we know about visualizing data (in general)

  • there is quite some basic research on visualizing information
  • for example using position (dot plot) it is easier estimating the mean than using areas
  • these results give us first ideas of what to expect
  • however, when plotting ES, several of these phenomena come together: most plots use position AND length AND area

Statistical Analyses

  • approximate adjusted fractional Bayes factors (Hoijtink et al., 2019)

Benchmarking

H3.1: \(\mu(sens)_{noBench} < \mu(sens)_{Bench}\)

H3.2: \(\mu(acc)_{noBench} < \mu(acc)_{Bench}\)

H3.3: \(\mu(inf)_{noBench} < \mu(inf)_{Bench}\)

H3.4: \(\mu(diff)_{noBench} > \mu(diff)_{Bench}\)
